@ENDNODE
@NODE install "StopMenu Documentation - Installation"


@{b}5. Installation@{ub}


The suggested way to install the program is by using the supplied installer
script. In case you either don't trust automatic installations or the
installation for any reason didn't work for you, or you maybe just want to
know, what the installer does, I described the complete installation procedure
below.

1. Create a new drawer called @{b}StopMenu@{ub} somewhere on your hard disk.

2. Replace the icon for this new drawer with
   @{b}StopMenuInstall/external/StopMenu.info@{ub}.

3. Assign @{b}StopMenu:@{ub} to this new drawer. Don't forget to write this new assign
   to your @{b}S:User_startup@{ub} file.

4. Copy the contents of @{b}StopMenuInstall/all@{ub} to @{b}StopMenu:@{ub}.

5. Rename either the @{b}StopMenu:glowicons@{ub} or the @{b}StopMenu:newicons@{ub} drawer to
   @{b}StopMenu:icons@{ub}. By doing this you select which icons you want to use.

6. Copy @{b}StopMenuInstall/external/StopMenuStarter.info@{ub} to @{b}SYS:WBstartup@{ub}.

7. Copy @{b}StopMenu.menus@{ub} and @{b}StopMenu.prefs@{ub} from @{b}StopMenuInstall/external@{ub} to
   @{b}StopMenu:@{ub} if you don't yet have your own modified version of these two files
   (ie. if you are a new user).

8. Copy the contents of @{b}StopMenuInstall/libs@{ub} to @{b}LIBS:@{ub}. Check the library
   versions before copying.

9. Copy the contents of @{b}StopMenuInstall/fonts@{ub} to @{b}FONTS:@{ub}.


@ENDNODE
@NODE usage "StopMenu Documentation - Usage"


@{b}6. Usage@{ub}


The StopMenu software package consists of four programs, each with their own
special functionality. You can find the instructions for all of them in the
following sections:

6.1. @{"StopMenu" LINK menu}
6.2. @{"Prefs" LINK prefs}
6.3. @{"MenusEditor" LINK editor}
6.4. @{"StopMeter" LINK meter}


@ENDNODE
@NODE menu "StopMenu Documentation - StopMenu Usage"


@{b}6.1. StopMenu@{ub}


You can find the StopMenu bar at the bottom of the screen. According to your
@{"settings" LINK prefs} it is visible all the time or it appears when you move your mouse to
the bottom of the screen.

The bar consists of five buttons (each of them can be turned on or off) and a
clock display (which can also be turned off). By clicking on the buttons you
open the following menus:

@{b}Stop button:@{ub}
  This menu contains programs installed on you computer. You can modify it by
  using the @{"Prefs" LINK prefs} program or by @{"changing the StopMenu:StopMenu.prefs file" LINK format} in
  your favourite text editor.

@{b}Commodities button:@{ub}
  Using this menu you can control your system commodities. The available
  actions for every commodity are:
  - @{b}Kill@{ub}:     Removes the commodity from your system.
  - @{b}Activate@{ub}: Enables the commodity functions.
  - @{b}DeAct.@{ub}:   Disables the commodity functions.
  - @{b}Show@{ub}:     Opens the commodity GUI.
  - @{b}Hide@{ub}:     Closes the commodity GUI.

@{b}Preferences button:@{ub}
  This menu contains items for direct starting of your preferences programs
  (found in SYS:Prefs). The ones installed there by the OS (3.1 only, 3.5 is
  not supported yet) are in the @{b}System@{ub} submenu, the rest of them are in the
  @{b}User@{ub} submenu. They are listed in alphabetical order.

@{b}Screens button:@{ub}
  This menu lists all currently opened screens. For each of them the following
  options are available:
  - @{b}To front@{ub}:    Moves the screen to front.
  - @{b}To back@{ub}:     Moves the screen to back.
  - @{b}Remove@{ub}:      Hides the screen and removes it from memory. This function is
                 very dangerous, you shouldn't use it if you don't know what
                 you're doing.
  - @{b}Save as IFF@{ub}: Saves the screen as an IFF file. It opens a requester for
                 selecting the filename.

@{b}WBWindows button:@{ub}
  This menu lists all curently opened windows on Workbench screen. For each of
  them the following options are available:
  - @{b}To front@{ub}: Moves the window to front.
  - @{b}To back@{ub}:  Moves the window to back.
  - @{b}Activate@{ub}: Activates window.
  - @{b}Close@{ub}:    Closes the window as if you clicked the close gadget.
  - @{b}Remove@{ub}:   Hides the window and removes it from memory. This function is very
              dangerous, you shouldn't use it if you don't know what you're
              doing.

@{b}Clock display:@{ub}
  It displays the current time. By clicking on it you start the @{"StopMeter" LINK meter}
  program.


@ENDNODE
@NODE prefs "StopMenu Documentation - Prefs Usage"


@{b}6.2. Prefs@{ub}


The Prefs window consists of three main parts. On the left there's a listview
from where you can select the group of options you're interested in. These
options then appear on the right. At the bottom there are four buttons with
the following meaning:

- @{b}Save:@{ub}    Saves all the options and activates them if @{"StopMenu" LINK menu} is started.
- @{b}About:@{ub}   Opens the about box with program information.
- @{b}Iconify:@{ub} Iconifies the Prefs program.
- @{b}Quit:@{ub}    Quits the Prefs program without saving the options.

In the groups the following options are available:

@{b}Information group:@{ub}
  This group displays basic program and registration information. If the program
  is already registered, the name of the registered user is displayed,
  otherwise the @{b}Register now...@{ub} button is displayed there. This button opens
  the @{"registration information" LINK register} in this guide.

@{b}Colours group:@{ub}
  In this group you can modify the colours used by the StopMenu program by
  either directly entering the hexadecimal value of the new color or by using
  the red, green and blue colour sliders on the right. The colours are used in
  the following places:
  - @{b}MenuBack:@{ub} menu background colour
  - @{b}BarBack:@{ub}  button background colour
  - @{b}Selected:@{ub} selected menu item colour
  - @{b}Shine:@{ub}    shine frame colour
  - @{b}Shadow:@{ub}   shadow frame colour

@{b}Appearance group:@{ub}
  In this group you can activate or deactivate several features of the StopMenu
  program. Available gadgets have the following meaning:
  - @{b}StopMenu:@{ub}           Turns on or off the Stop button.
  - @{b}Commodities:@{ub}        Turns on or off the Commodities button.
  - @{b}Preferences:@{ub}        Turns on or off the Preferences button.
  - @{b}Screens:@{ub}            Turns on or off the Screens button.
  - @{b}Windows:@{ub}            Turns on or off the WBWindows button.
  - @{b}Clock:@{ub}              Turns on or off the clock display.
  - @{b}Background:@{ub}         Turns on or off the background pattern.
  - @{b}Items border:@{ub}       Turns on or off the border around the selected menu
                        item.
  - @{b}Don't hide bar:@{ub}     If selected, the StopMenu program will be visible all
                        the time.
  - @{b}Popup delay:@{ub}        If selected, the appearance and disappearance of the
                        StopMenu will be delayed a bit. This option doesn't
                        have any meaning if @{b}Don't hide bar@{ub} is selected.
  - @{b}Animation:@{ub}          If selected, the appearance and disappearance of the
                        StopMenu will be animated. This option doesn't have any
                        meaning if @{b}Don't hide bar@{ub} is selected.
  - @{b}Speed:@{ub}              Sets the speed of the animation to @{b}Slow@{ub}, @{b}Med.@{ub} or @{b}Fast@{ub}.
                        This option doesn't have any meaning if @{b}Animation@{ub} is not
                        selected.
  - @{b}Background:@{ub}         Here you can select an IFF picture file for the StopMenu
                        background by either entering the path in the string
                        gadget or by clicking the @{b}?@{ub} button and selecting it in
                        the file requester.
  - @{b}All public screens:@{ub} If selected, the StopMenu should appear on every public
                        screen open in your system.
  - @{b}Remap backgr.:@{ub}      If selected, the background picture colours will be
                        remmaped to the current screen colours. This option
                        should be checked if you want to assure as good a
                        background display as possible.

@{b}Hotkeys group:@{ub}
  In this group you can select the program hotkeys and some other commodity
  related program settings. The following settings are available:
  - @{b}Quit key:@{ub}      The hotkey for quitting the StopMenu program.
  - @{b}Prefs key:@{ub}     The hotkey for starting the Prefs program.
  - @{b}Restart key:@{ub}   The hotkey for restarting the StopMenu program (which enables
                   any changes that might have been done to the @{"StopMenu.menus" LINK format}
                   file since the program was started). The StopMenu program is
                   also restarted when you press Save in either the Prefs or the
                   MenusEditor program.
  - @{b}Show/hide key:@{ub} The hotkey for displaying or hiding the StopMenu program.
  - @{b}Task priority:@{ub} The priority of the task running the StopMenu.
  - @{b}Popup delay:@{ub}   The delay before the StopMenu appears if @{b}Popup delay@{ub} in the
                   previous group is selected. Otherwise this setting is
                   ignored.
  - @{b}Close delay:@{ub}   The delay before the StopMenu disappears if @{b}Popup delay@{ub} in
                   the previous group is selected. Otherwise this setting is
                   ignored.

@{b}Commodities group:@{ub}
  In this group you can select which active commodities you don't want to appear
  in Commodities menu. The not displayed commodities are listed in the listview
  which you can manage with the following two buttons:
  - @{b}Add:@{ub}    Adds a new commodity to the listview. You can change its default
            name by selecting it, then renaming it in the string gadget below
            and finally confirming it by pressing RETURN. You can use the same
            procedure for renaming a listview entry at any time.
  - @{b}Remove:@{ub} Removes the currently selected commodity from the listview.

@{b}Preferences group:@{ub}
  In this group you can select which programs from SYS:Prefs you don't want to
  appear in Preferences menu. The not displayed programs are listed in the
  listview which you can manage with the following two buttons:
  - @{b}Add:@{ub}    Adds a new program to the listview. You can change its default name
            by selecting it, then renaming it in the string gadget below and
            finally confirming it by pressing RETURN. You can use the same
            procedure for renaming a listview entry at any time.
  - @{b}Remove:@{ub} Removes the currently selected program from the listview.

@{b}Screens group:@{ub}
  In this group you can select which screens you don't want to appear in Screens
  menu. The not displayed screens are listed in the listview which you can
  manage with the following two buttons:
  - @{b}Add:@{ub}    Adds a new screen to the listview. You can change its default name
            by selecting it, then renaming it in the string gadget below and
            finally confirming it by pressing RETURN. You can use the same
            procedure for renaming a listview entry at any time.
  - @{b}Remove:@{ub} Removes the currently selected screen from the listview.

@{b}Windows group:@{ub}
  In this group you can select which windows on the WB screen you don't want to
  appear in WBWindows menu. The not displayed windows are listed in the listview
  which you can manage with the following two buttons:
  - @{b}Add:@{ub}    Adds a new window to the listview. You can change its default name
            by selecting it, then renaming it in the string gadget below and
            finally confirming it by pressing RETURN. You can use the same
            procedure for renaming a listview entry at any time.
  - @{b}Remove:@{ub} Removes the currently selected window from the listview.

@{b}Graphics group:@{ub}
  In this group you can change the appearance of text and frames for different
  parts of StopMenu. You can select the style of the text (@{b}Normal@{ub}, @{b}Bold@{ub}, @{b}Shadow@{ub},
  @{b}Outline@{ub} and @{b}Outline2@{ub}) and the frames (@{b}Single@{ub}, @{b}Double@{ub}, @{b}Win95@{ub} and @{b}Xen@{ub}) for the
  @{b}Menus@{ub}, the @{b}Stop button@{ub}, the @{b}Other buttons@{ub}, the @{b}Clock@{ub} display and the StopMenu
  @{b}Bar@{ub} itself. Below these cycle gadgets there are a few more gadgets:
  - @{b}Font:@{ub}        Here you should enter the name of the font for the StopMenu (in
                 the first string gadget) and its size (in the second integer
                 gadget). You can also click the ? button to the right and
                 select it in the font requester.
  - @{b}Item height:@{ub} This value sets the height of the menu items. If it is smaller
                 than the size of the height of the icons you are using, the
                 program will automatically increase it accordingly.
  - @{b}Icons width:@{ub} This value sets the width of the space provided for the icons
                 in front of the menu items' text. If it smaller than the width
                 of the icons you are using, the program will automatically
                 increase it accordingly.

The Prefs window also has a menu attached. The following actions are available
from the menus:

@{b}Project:@{ub}
  @{b}Load...@{ub}    - Opens a file requester in which you can select a prefs file to
               load the program settings from. Your current settings can be
               loaded from StopMenu:StopMenu.prefs.
  @{b}Save as...@{ub} - Opens a file requester in which you can select the name of the
               prefs file for saving the program settings to. The program loads
               its settings from StopMenu:StopMenu.prefs.
  @{b}About...@{ub}   - Opens the about box with program information.
  @{b}Iconify@{ub}    - Iconifies the Prefs program.
  @{b}Quit@{ub}       - Quits the Prefs program without saving the options.


@ENDNODE
@NODE editor "StopMenu Documentation - MenusEditor Usage"


@{b}6.3. MenusEditor@{ub}


This program's function is editing the contents of the Stop menu. The window is
separated into two parts. The left part displays your menu in a listview, in the
right part there are gadgets for modifying the menu.

With the following buttons you can navigate through your menus (all actions are
performed on the active listview item):

- @{b}Enter:@{ub}  Enters current submenu.
- @{b}Back:@{ub}   Moves from the current menu one level up.
- @{b}Up:@{ub}     Moves the active menu item one position up.
- @{b}Down:@{ub}   Moves the active menu item one position down.
- @{b}Add:@{ub}    Adds a new menu item.
- @{b}Delete:@{ub} Deletes the active menu item.

To the right of these buttons there are gadgets for changing the properties of
the active menu item:

- @{b}Name:@{ub}  The name of the menu item. This one will be displayed in the menu.
- @{b}File:@{ub}  The name of the file (with complete path) which is going to be started
         by selecting this menu item. By clicking on a @{b}?@{ub} on the right you can
         open a file requester.
- @{b}Icon:@{ub}  The icon that is going to be displayed in front of the menu item text.
         Instead of typing in its number you can also select the icon from the
         Icons gadget described below.
- @{b}Type:@{ub}  The type of the menu item, one of the following:
         @{b}CLI@{ub}     - The file will be started as if you started it from the Shell.
         @{b}WB@{ub}      - The file will be started as if you clicked on its icon in WB.
         @{b}Script@{ub}  - The file be executed as a script.
         @{b}Menu@{ub}    - The menu item represents a submenu.
         @{b}Command@{ub} - The menu item represents an internal command. You can select
                   it by clicking on the @{b}?@{ub} right to the @{b}File@{ub} gadget and choosing
                   the prefered command from the list.
         @{b}Bar@{ub}     - The menu item is a separator bar.
         @{b}Space@{ub}   - The menu item is an increased space between the neighbouring
                   menu items.
- @{b}Icons:@{ub} These custom gadget displays your available icons. You can select one
         by just clicking on it. By clicking on the arrows at the side you can
         move the bar with the icons to the left or to the right, by clicking
         on the @{b}F@{ub} you can move to the beggining of this bar and by clicking in
         the @{b}L@{ub} you move it to the end.

Below these gadgets there are three buttons with following functions:

- @{b}Save:@{ub}    Saves the menu and activates it if StopMenu is started.
- @{b}Iconify:@{ub} Iconifies the MenusEditor program.
- @{b}Quit:@{ub}    Quits the MenusEditor program without saving the changes in the menu.

The window also has a menu bar attached. By selecting the menu items the
following actions can be performed:

@{b}Project:@{ub}
  @{b}Load...@{ub}    - Opens a file requester in which you can select a menus file to
               load the Stop Menu contents from. Your currently used menu can be
               loaded from StopMenu:StopMenu.prefs.
  @{b}Save as...@{ub} - Opens a file requester in which you can select the name of the
               menus file for saving the Stop menu contents to. The program
               loads the menu from StopMenu:StopMenu.menus.
  @{b}About...@{ub}   - Opens the about box with program information.
  @{b}Iconify@{ub}    - Iconifies the MenusEditor program.
  @{b}Quit@{ub}       - Quits the MenusEditor program without saving the menu.

@{b}Edit:@{ub}
  @{b}Enter@{ub}  - Enters current submenu.
  @{b}Back@{ub}   - Moves from the current menu one level up.
  @{b}Up@{ub}     - Moves the active menu item one position up.
  @{b}Down@{ub}   - Moves the active menu item one position down.
  @{b}Add@{ub}    - Adds a new menu item.
  @{b}Delete@{ub} - Deletes the active menu item.


@ENDNODE
@NODE meter "StopMenu Documentation - StopMeter Usage"


@{b}6.4. StopMeter@{ub}


This program provides information on how busy your computer is. In the titlebar
the date and the current time are displayed. In the centre part of the window
three histograms are displayed which show how busy your @{b}CPU@{ub} is and how much of
the @{b}Chip@{ub} and @{b}Fast@{ub} RAM is used. At the bottom are two buttons:

- @{b}Snapshot:@{ub} Saves the current position of the window.
- @{b}Quit:@{ub}     Quits the StopMeter program.


@ENDNODE
@NODE advanced "StopMenu Documentation - Advanced topics"


@{b}7. Advanced Topics@{ub}


This section covers some of the issues for more advanced users who like more
control on how the program works. At the moment two topics are available.

7.1. @{"StopMenu.menus file format" LINK format}
7.2. @{"Creating custom icons" LINK icons}


@ENDNODE
@NODE format "StopMenu Documentation - StopMenu.menus File Format"


@{b}7.1. StopMenu.menus File Format@{ub}


In case you like it better to edit the menus description file manually or if
you just want to know how it is constructed even if you generate it with
MenusEditor, then this section is the one for you. In the following lines
the file format is described using the Backus-Naur Formalism (@{b}\n@{ub} denotes a
newline).

@{b}MenusDescription = Comment\n<BEGIN>\nMenuDesc{MenuDesc}<END>\nComment@{ub}

  @{b}<BEGIN>@{ub} marks the beggining of the menus description, @{b}<END>@{ub} marks the end of
  it. Outside these two there is place for @{b}Comment@{ub} without any limitations as
  those lines are not parsed at all.

@{b}MenuDescr = MENU Comment\nMenuItem{MenuItem}@{ub}

  The @{b}MENU@{ub} keyword denotes the start of the particular menu. Behind it you can
  write any @{b}Comment@{ub} you want as long as you don't enter a newline.

@{b}MenuItem = (BAR|SPACE|ITEM Params)\n@{ub}

  Three types of menu items exist: @{b}BAR@{ub} is a separator bar, @{b}SPACE@{ub} is increased
  space between two neighbouring menu items and @{b}ITEM@{ub} is a real menu item.

@{b}Params = Name,(SubMenu|Command|Program)@{ub}

  @{b}Name@{ub} is the name of the item you want to be displayed in the menu.

@{b}SubMenu = ,Icon,MENU,MenuId@{ub}

  @{b}Icon@{ub} is the number of the icon that is going to be displayed in front of the
  menu name (infact it si the filename of the icon in the StopMenu:icons
  drawer). @{b}MENU@{ub} denotes that this item represents a submenu. @{b}MenuId@{ub} is the
  number of the menu attached to this item (the number is set by the position
  at which the menu is described in the file: the first menu described has
  number 1, the second number 2 etc.).

@{b}Command = KeyWord,Icon,COMMAND@{ub}

  @{b}Icon@{ub} is the number of the icon that is going to be displayed in front of the
  menu name (infact it si the filename of the icon in the StopMenu:icons
  drawer). @{b}COMMAND@{ub} denotes that these item will execute one of the program
  internal commands.

@{b}KeyWord = (QUIT|RUNPREFS|RUNEDITOR|RUNMETER|RESTART|REBOOT|SHOW|HIDE)@{ub}

  The following internal commands are available:
  - @{b}QUIT@{ub}:      Quits StopMenu program.
  - @{b}RUNPREFS@{ub}:  Starts the Prefs program.
  - @{b}RUNEDITOR@{ub}: Starts the MenusEditor program.
  - @{b}RUNMETER@{ub}:  Starts the StopMeter program.
  - @{b}RESTART@{ub}:   Restarts the StopMenu and reloads all the settings.
  - @{b}REBOOT@{ub}:    Reboots your Amiga.
  - @{b}SHOW@{ub}:      Displays the StopMenu interface.
  - @{b}HIDE@{ub}:      Hides the StopMenu interface.

@{b}Program = Path,Icon,Type@{ub}

  @{b}Icon@{ub} is the number of the icon that is going to be displayed in front of the
  menu name (infact it si the filename of the icon in the StopMenu:icons
  drawer). @{b}Path@{ub} is the complete path to the file that is going to be started by
  selecting the menu item.

@{b}Type = (WB|CLI|SCRIPT)@{ub}

  This type selects the way in which the file is going to be started:
  - @{b}CLI:@{ub}    The file will be started as if you started it from the Shell.
  - @{b}WB:@{ub}     The file will be started as if you clicked on its icon in WB.
  - @{b}Script:@{ub} The file be executed as a script.


@ENDNODE
@NODE icons "StopMenu Documentation - Creating Custom Icons"


@{b}7.2. Creating Custom Icons@{ub}


There is quite an amount of icons already included in the StopMenu distribution,
but it is still possible that you would like more of them and want to include
some of your own. This is of course possible. There are just a few things you
have to take care of.

1. All icons have to be put in the @{b}StopMenu:icons@{ub} directory.
2. They have to be in NewIcon format (ie. the best way to create them is by
   using the InjectBrush tool from NewIcon archive).
3. The program recognises the icons only if they are named with a number and if
   the numbers continue sequentionaly (your should start naming your icons where
   the distributed ones stop, i.e. 95 if you're using NewIcon style or 104 if
   you're using GlowIcon style).

You can also change any of the already supplied icons to your taste, i.e. even
the first 94 or 103 icons in the archive. In the @{b}StopMenu:icons/program@{ub} drawer
there are all other program icons. They can also be changed, but this isn't
really supported, so you do it at your own risk (watch out the size as the bar
itself is not resizable).


@ENDNODE
